# Beads Task Tracking Rules

## The One Rule That Covers Everything

**`bd` is the single source of truth for all work items.** No exceptions.

---

## What Goes Where

| Content | Where it lives |
|---|---|
| Tasks, bugs, epics, spikes | `bd create` |
| AI planning docs, session notes, exploration output | `history/` directory |
| Project knowledge, decisions, handoffs | `memory/` directory |
| Source code | repo |

### Never

- ❌ Create markdown TODO lists (`TODO.md`, `TASKS.md`, checklists in any `.md` file)
- ❌ Use external issue trackers (GitHub Issues, Jira, Linear, Notion) alongside `bd`
- ❌ Duplicate tasks across systems — one task, one place, always `bd`
- ❌ Drop planning docs in the repo root — use `history/` or `memory/`

---

## Starting Work

```bash
# Always check this first — never ask "what should I work on?" without running it
bd ready

# Claim before touching any code
bd update <id> --claim
```

`bd ready` shows tasks with no open blockers. If it returns nothing, create or unblock tasks before writing a single line.

---

## Creating Tasks

```bash
# Standard task
bd create "Title" -p 1

# Priorities: 0=critical  1=high  2=medium  3=low
bd create "Fix checkout crash on empty cart" -p 0
bd create "Add unit tests for auth middleware" -p 1
bd create "Improve error message copy" -p 3
```

### Link discovered work with `discovered-from`

When a task reveals follow-up work (during exploration, code review, test failure, or AI analysis), link the new task back to the one that surfaced it:

```bash
# Original task
bd create "Explore authentication flows" -p 1
# → bd-a1b2

# Work discovered while doing bd-a1b2
bd create "Token refresh endpoint missing CSRF protection" -p 0
# → bd-c3d4

# Link: c3d4 was discovered while working on a1b2
bd dep add bd-c3d4 bd-a1b2 --type discovered-from

# More examples
bd dep add bd-e5f6 bd-a1b2 --type discovered-from  # another finding from same task
bd dep add bd-g7h8 bd-c3d4 --type discovered-from  # finding from a finding
```

This creates an audit trail: you can always trace any task back to the work that surfaced it.

---

## Programmatic Use (`--json`)

When AI agents parse `bd` output to make decisions, **always use `--json`**:

```bash
# ✅ machine-readable
bd ready --json
bd list --json
bd show <id> --json
bd list --status in_progress --json

# Parse with jq
bd ready --json | jq '.[].title'
bd ready --json | jq '.[] | select(.priority == 0)'

# ❌ never parse plain-text output
bd ready   # human display only — format may change
```

Use `--json` in any script, justfile target, or AI reasoning step that reads `bd` output programmatically.

---

## Completing Work

```bash
bd update <id> --status done

# Create follow-up tasks for anything discovered
bd create "Follow-up: ..." -p N
bd dep add <new-id> <done-id> --type discovered-from
```

---

## Storing AI Planning Output

All AI-generated planning documents, session notes, analysis outputs, and exploration artifacts go in `history/`:

```
history/
├── 2026-02-26-auth-exploration.md     # exploratory session output
├── 2026-02-26-pm-prd-v1.md            # PM's PRD draft before it's approved
├── 2026-02-27-security-findings.md    # security engineer's raw findings
└── 2026-02-27-architect-spike.md      # architecture spike notes
```

File naming: `YYYY-MM-DD-<description>.md`

`history/` is append-only — never edit existing files, only add new ones. Add `history/` to `.gitignore` if it contains sensitive findings; commit it for team visibility otherwise.

---

## Dependency Types

```bash
bd dep add <child> <parent>                         # child is blocked by parent (default)
bd dep add <finding> <source> --type discovered-from  # finding surfaced during source
bd dep add <dup> <original> --type duplicates         # dup is a duplicate of original
bd dep add <new> <old> --type supersedes              # new replaces old approach
```

---

## justfile targets

Add these to every project justfile:

```justfile
# Show unblocked tasks — run before any session
tasks:
    @bd ready --json | jq -r '.[] | "\(.id)\t\(.priority)\t\(.title)"'

# Create a task (usage: just task "Title" [priority 0-3])
task title priority="1":
    bd create "{{title}}" -p {{priority}}

# Claim a task
claim id:
    bd update {{id}} --claim

# Mark done and show what's next
done id:
    bd update {{id}} --status done
    @echo "Next unblocked tasks:"
    @bd ready --json | jq -r '.[0:3] | .[] | "\(.id) \(.title)"'
```

---

## Summary

| Rule | Why |
|---|---|
| `bd ready` before every session | Prevents working on blocked or deprioritized items |
| `--json` for programmatic output | Plain-text format is unstable; JSON is a contract |
| `discovered-from` links | Full audit trail from any task back to the work that surfaced it |
| All tasks in `bd` | One system = no sync overhead, no duplication, no lost context |
| Planning docs in `history/` | Keeps repo root clean; docs are findable but not clutter |
| No markdown TODO lists | They immediately go stale and duplicate `bd` state |
